var documenterSearchIndex = {"docs":
[{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#File-formats","page":"File formats","text":"JASCOSpectrum reads the CSV exports produced by JASCO's FTIR, Raman, and V-series UV-Vis spectrometers. All three instruments share the same basic layout, but they differ in delimiter, encoding habits, and which header fields they actually populate. This page documents what the parser expects, what it fills in when a field is missing, and the known limitations of the current implementation.","title":"File formats"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Common-structure","page":"File formats","text":"Every supported JASCO file follows this layout:\n\nA header of delimited KEY<delim>VALUE pairs, one per line.\nA data section of delimited x,y pairs, one per line.\nA footer of further KEY<delim>VALUE pairs (measurement settings, operator name, instrument serial number, etc.), separated from the data by a blank line.\n\nThe parser captures both the header and the footer into s.metadata. See Footer metadata below for the section markers it skips and the Japanese→English alias behavior.","title":"Common structure"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Per-instrument-variants","page":"File formats","text":"","title":"Per-instrument variants"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#FTIR","page":"File formats","text":"Comma-delimited. DATA TYPE is set to INFRARED SPECTRUM and XUNITS is typically 1/CM.\n\nTITLE,\nDATA TYPE,INFRARED SPECTRUM\nDATE,23/01/11\nTIME,16:49:31\nXUNITS,1/CM\nYUNITS,ABSORBANCE\nXYDATA\n999.9101,0.572538","title":"FTIR"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Raman","page":"File formats","text":"Also comma-delimited. DATA TYPE is RAMAN SPECTRUM and XUNITS is typically 1/CM (Raman shift).\n\nTITLE,C1\nDATA TYPE,RAMAN SPECTRUM\nDATE,24/11/05\nXUNITS,1/CM\nYUNITS,INTENSITY\nXYDATA\n545.8049,199","title":"Raman"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#UV-Vis-(V-series,-e.g.-V-730)","page":"File formats","text":"Tab-delimited, and DATA TYPE is emitted blank. XUNITS is NANOMETERS.\n\nTITLE<TAB>\nDATA TYPE<TAB>\nDATE<TAB>26/02/12\nSPECTROMETER/DATA SYSTEM<TAB>JASCO Corp., V-730, Rev. 1.00\nXUNITS<TAB>NANOMETERS\nYUNITS<TAB>ABSORBANCE\nXYDATA\n1000<TAB>-0.0983645\n\nBecause DATA TYPE is blank, UV-Vis files cannot be recognised by the string \"UV/VIS SPECTRUM\" alone — see UV-Vis classification below.","title":"UV-Vis (V-series, e.g. V-730)"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Encoding","page":"File formats","text":"The default encoding is SHIFT-JIS, which is what JASCO instruments emit natively. This is necessary for the Japanese metadata keys that appear in some exports, such as 機種名 (\"model name\"). Pass any StringEncodings.Encoding via the encoding keyword to override:\n\nusing StringEncodings\ns = JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\"; encoding=enc\"UTF-8\")","title":"Encoding"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Metadata-fields","page":"File formats","text":"Header and footer entries are both stored in s.metadata::Dict{String,Any}. A handful of header keys are also given dedicated struct fields:\n\nHeader key Struct field Notes\nTITLE s.title \nDATE + TIME s.date Parsed as a single DateTime; see below\nSPECTROMETER/DATA SYSTEM s.spectrometer Falls back to 機種名 if the English key is absent\nDATA TYPE s.datatype Blank on V-series UV-Vis\nXUNITS s.xunits \nYUNITS s.yunits \n\nThe following keys are common but are left in s.metadata only — they are not promoted to struct fields:\n\nHeader key Typical value\nORIGIN JASCO\nOWNER Operator name (often blank)\nLOCALE Windows LCID (e.g. 1041 = Japanese)\nFIRSTX First x value as a string\nLASTX Last x value\nNPOINTS Number of data points\nDELTAX X-step size (sign indicates direction)\nRESOLUTION Instrument resolution (often blank)\nFIRSTY, MAXY, MINY Y summary statistics\n\nAll values are stored as the raw String read from the file.","title":"Metadata fields"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Missing-field-defaults","page":"File formats","text":"To make every JASCOSpectrum field have a definite value, missing header keys fall back to placeholder values rather than missing:\n\nStruct field Default when key is missing\ntitle \"Untitled\"\nspectrometer \"Unknown\"\ndatatype \"Unknown\"\nxunits \"cm-1\"\nyunits \"Abs\"\ndate DateTime(2000)\n\nCheck haskey(s.metadata, \"RESOLUTION\") when you need to distinguish a genuinely recorded value from a missing one.","title":"Missing-field defaults"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Date-format","page":"File formats","text":"JASCO writes DATE as yy/mm/dd and TIME as HH:MM:SS. The parser concatenates them and prepends \"20\" to form a four-digit year before parsing with dateformat\"yy/mm/ddTHH:MM:SS\".","title":"Date format"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#UV-Vis-classification","page":"File formats","text":"Because V-series UV-Vis exports leave DATA TYPE blank, a simple string compare against \"UV/VIS SPECTRUM\" is not enough. isuvvis uses a small heuristic:\n\nIf s.datatype == \"UV/VIS SPECTRUM\", return true immediately.\nOtherwise, if s.datatype is non-empty, return false (it is a different instrument).\nIf s.datatype is blank, require s.xunits == \"NANOMETERS\" and the full wavelength range to fall within 100 ≤ x ≤ 3500 nm.\n\nThe wavelength window is deliberately wider than the visible range so that UV-Vis/NIR extensions are still recognised, but narrow enough to exclude IR data that happens to be expressed in other units. A file with blank DATA TYPE and XUNITS = \"1/CM\" will not be classified as UV-Vis.\n\nisftir and israman are strict string matches against \"INFRARED SPECTRUM\" and \"RAMAN SPECTRUM\" respectively and do not need a heuristic.","title":"UV-Vis classification"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Footer-metadata","page":"File formats","text":"JASCO exports include a second metadata block after the data section. The parser detects it by the blank line that separates it from the data, and captures every KEY<delim>VALUE row it finds there into s.metadata alongside the header keys.\n\nFooter information:\n\nFTIR footers typically include detector type, integration count, resolution, apodization, zero-filling, scan speed, gain, aperture, and light source.\nRaman footers often include acquisition settings like laser wavelength, laser power, grating, slit, objective lens, CCD temperature, and the rejection filter.\nV-series UV-Vis footers include a [測定情報] (\"measurement information\") section with model name, serial number, photometric mode, bandwidth, response, scan speed, and light source, often followed by a [付属品情報] (\"accessory information\") section.","title":"Footer metadata"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#Section-markers-and-decorations","page":"File formats","text":"Footer blocks frequently include bracketed section headers like [測定情報], [コメント情報], [データ情報], and [付属品情報]. JASCO FTIR exports also prefix the footer with a literal ##### Extended Information line. None of these decorations are stored — only the actual KEY<delim>VALUE rows are kept.","title":"Section markers and decorations"},{"category":"section","location":"guide/file-formats/#JapaneseEnglish-aliases","page":"File formats","text":"JASCO FTIR and V-series UV-Vis exports use Japanese keys in the footer (e.g. 積算回数, 光源, 検出器). By default the parser preserves the original Japanese key and adds an English-aliased entry resolving to the same value:\n\njulia> s = JASCOSpectrum(\"ftir.csv\");\n\njulia> s.metadata[\"積算回数\"]\n\"16\"\n\njulia> s.metadata[\"Accumulation\"]\n\"16\"\n\nA small set of Japanese values is also translated. For example, 光源 = 標準光源 becomes:\n\njulia> s.metadata[\"光源\"]\n\"Standard light source\"\n\njulia> s.metadata[\"Light source\"]\n\"Standard light source\"\n\nPass translate=false to disable both translations and keep only the originals:\n\ns = JASCOSpectrum(\"ftir.csv\"; translate=false)\ns.metadata[\"光源\"]                   # \"標準光源\"\nhaskey(s.metadata, \"Light source\")  # false\n\nIf you encounter a Japanese term that isn't yet mapped, a PR adding an entry is welcome.","title":"Japanese→English aliases"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Public-API","page":"Library","text":"Only exported types and functions are considered part of the public API. Raw header fields not covered by the exposed struct fields are still available through s.metadata.","title":"Public API"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Index","page":"Library","text":"Pages = [\"public.md\"]","title":"Index"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Reading-files","page":"Library","text":"","title":"Reading files"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Types","page":"Library","text":"","title":"Types"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Type-predicates-and-Base-methods","page":"Library","text":"","title":"Type predicates and Base methods"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Transmittance-absorbance-conversions","page":"Library","text":"","title":"Transmittance ↔ absorbance conversions"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Plotting-helpers","page":"Library","text":"xlabel and ylabel produce nicely formatted axis labels (e.g. \"Wavenumber (cm⁻¹)\", \"Transmittance (%)\") from a spectrum's units. They work without any plotting backend loaded.","title":"Plotting helpers"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Plotting-with-Makie","page":"Library","text":"When Makie is loaded, plot(s) is available via a package extension. Load a backend first (using CairoMakie or using GLMakie):\n\nusing JASCOFiles, CairoMakie\n\ns = JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\")\nfig, ax, ln = plot(s)\nfig, ax, ln = plot(s; color = :tomato)\nfig, ax, ln = plot(s; axis = (xreversed = false,))\n\nAxis defaults are filled from the spectrum:\n\nxlabel from xlabel(s)\nylabel from ylabel(s)\ntitle from s.title\nxreversed = isftir(s) (standard IR orientation: wavenumber decreases left-to-right)\n\nPass an axis NamedTuple to override any of these. Other keyword arguments are forwarded to Makie.lines.\n\nThe extension also hooks Makie.convert_arguments, so lines(s), scatter(s), and lines!(ax, s) work directly without going through s.x/s.y.","title":"Plotting with Makie"},{"category":"section","location":"lib/public/#Tables.jl-integration","page":"Library","text":"A JASCOSpectrum implements the Tables.jl column-access interface with two columns, :x and :y. Any package that consumes a Tables-compatible source works directly:\n\nusing JASCOFiles, DataFrames\n\ns = JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\")\ndf = DataFrame(s)        # columns :x and :y\n\nusing JASCOFiles, CSV\n\nCSV.write(\"sample_xy.csv\", JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\"))\n\nThe extension loads automatically when both JASCOFiles and a Tables.jl-compatible package (DataFrames, CSV, Arrow, …) are loaded in the same session — no explicit using Tables required. Column names are intentionally generic; if you want labelled output, rename after conversion (e.g. rename!(df, :x => :wavenumber, :y => :absorbance)).","title":"Tables.jl integration"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.AbstractJASCOSpectrum","page":"Library","text":"AbstractJASCOSpectrum\n\nAbstract type for JASCO spectra.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.AbstractJASCOSpectrum"},{"category":"type","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.JASCOSpectrum","page":"Library","text":"JASCOSpectrum <: AbstractJASCOSpectrum\n\nRepresents a single spectrum parsed from a JASCO file.\n\nFields\n\ntitle::String: Title of the measurement.\ndate::DateTime: Date and time of the measurement.\nspectrometer::String: Name of the spectrometer instrument.\ndatatype::String: Type of spectrum (e.g. \"INFRARED SPECTRUM\", \"RAMAN SPECTRUM\").\nxunits::String: Units for the x-axis (e.g. \"cm-1\").\nyunits::String: Units for the y-axis (e.g. \"Abs\").\nx::Vector{Float64}: X-axis data points.\ny::Vector{Float64}: Y-axis data points.\nmetadata::Dict{String, Any}: Raw metadata dictionary from the file header.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.JASCOSpectrum"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.isftir-Tuple{AbstractJASCOSpectrum}","page":"Library","text":"isftir(s::AbstractJASCOSpectrum) -> Bool\n\nReturn true if the spectrum is an FTIR (infrared) spectrum.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.isftir"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.israman-Tuple{AbstractJASCOSpectrum}","page":"Library","text":"israman(s::AbstractJASCOSpectrum) -> Bool\n\nReturn true if the spectrum is a Raman spectrum.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.israman"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.isuvvis-Tuple{AbstractJASCOSpectrum}","page":"Library","text":"isuvvis(s::AbstractJASCOSpectrum) -> Bool\n\nReturn true if the spectrum is a UV-Vis (or UV-Vis/NIR) spectrum.\n\nSome JASCO instruments (e.g. the V-730) export files with a blank DATA TYPE field. In that case, the spectrum is classified as UV-Vis when xunits is \"NANOMETERS\" and the wavelength range falls within 100–3500 nm.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.isuvvis"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.absorbance_to_transmittance-Tuple{JASCOSpectrum}","page":"Library","text":"absorbance_to_transmittance(spec::JASCOSpectrum; percent=true)\n\nConvert a JASCOSpectrum from absorbance to transmittance using T = 10^(-A).\n\nReturns a new JASCOSpectrum with the y-axis converted to transmittance. Defaults to percent transmittance (percent=true, yunits=\"TRANSMITTANCE\"); pass percent=false for fractional transmittance (yunits=\"TRANSMITTANCE_FRAC\").\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.absorbance_to_transmittance"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.transmittance_to_absorbance-Tuple{JASCOSpectrum}","page":"Library","text":"transmittance_to_absorbance(spec::JASCOSpectrum; percent=true)\n\nConvert a JASCOSpectrum from transmittance to absorbance using A = -log10(T).\n\nJASCO instruments record percent transmittance (0–100) by default. Set percent=false if the y-data is already fractional transmittance (0–1).\n\nReturns a new JASCOSpectrum with the y-axis converted to absorbance and yunits set to \"ABS\".\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.transmittance_to_absorbance"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.xlabel-Tuple{AbstractJASCOSpectrum}","page":"Library","text":"xlabel(s::AbstractJASCOSpectrum) -> String\n\nReturn a human-readable x-axis label for s.\n\nExamples:\n\nFTIR with 1/CM      → \"Wavenumber (cm⁻¹)\"\nRaman with 1/CM     → \"Raman shift (cm⁻¹)\"\nUV-Vis with NANOMETERS → \"Wavelength (nm)\"\n\nUnits that aren't recognised fall back to a title-cased form of s.xunits.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.xlabel"},{"category":"method","location":"lib/public/#JASCOFiles.ylabel-Tuple{AbstractJASCOSpectrum}","page":"Library","text":"ylabel(s::AbstractJASCOSpectrum) -> String\n\nReturn a human-readable y-axis label for s.\n\nExamples:\n\nABSORBANCE / Abs  → \"Absorbance\"\nINTENSITY           → \"Intensity\"\nTRANSMITTANCE       → \"Transmittance (%)\"\nTRANSMITTANCE_FRAC  → \"Transmittance\"\n\nUnits that aren't recognised fall back to a title-cased form of s.yunits.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.ylabel"},{"category":"section","location":"#JASCOFiles.jl","page":"Introduction","text":"JASCOFiles.jl reads the CSV files exported from JASCO spectrometers (FTIR, Raman, and UV-Vis) into a JASCOSpectrum struct holding the x-axis (wavenumber or wavelength), the y-axis (absorbance, transmittance, or intensity), the recording date, the instrument name, etc. The full raw header is preserved in s.metadata.\n\nThe parser auto-detects the delimiter (comma for FTIR/Raman, tab for V-series UV-Vis) and decodes Japanese text encoding (SHIFT-JIS) by default, so the same JASCOSpectrum(path) call loads every file a JASCO instrument produces.\n\nThe package is deliberately small so that it loads quickly. Some basic operations are included for convenience, like transforming between absorbance and transmittance, or plotting a spectrum in one line when Makie is loaded.","title":"JASCOFiles.jl"},{"category":"section","location":"#Installation","page":"Introduction","text":"using Pkg\nPkg.add(\"JASCOFiles\")","title":"Installation"},{"category":"section","location":"#Reading-a-file","page":"Introduction","text":"Point JASCOSpectrum at a CSV exported from a JASCO spectrometer and you get a parsed struct back:\n\nusing JASCOFiles\n\ns = JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\")\n\nIn the REPL, the spectrum prints a compact summary:\n\njulia> s = JASCOSpectrum(\"ftir.csv\")\nJASCOSpectrum: INFRARED SPECTRUM\n  title:        \"My Sample\"\n  spectrometer: \"JASCO FT/IR-4700\"\n  date:         2023-01-11T16:49:31\n  xunits:       1/CM  (12447 points)\n  yunits:       ABSORBANCE\n  range:        999.9101 → 7000.335\n  metadata:     24 keys","title":"Reading a file"},{"category":"section","location":"#What's-in-a-spectrum","page":"Introduction","text":"The x- and y-axis data are plain Julia numeric arrays, and the common header fields are available directly on the struct:\n\ns.x          # wavenumbers, Raman shifts, or wavelengths\ns.y          # absorbance, transmittance, or intensity values\ns.xunits     # \"1/CM\", \"NANOMETERS\", ...\ns.yunits     # \"ABSORBANCE\", \"INTENSITY\", ...\ns.datatype   # \"INFRARED SPECTRUM\", \"RAMAN SPECTRUM\", \"UV/VIS SPECTRUM\", or \"\" for V-730\ns.title      # from the TITLE header field\ns.spectrometer\ns.date       # DateTime, parsed from DATE + TIME\n\nYou can also ask how many points the spectrum has with length(s).","title":"What's in a spectrum"},{"category":"section","location":"#Metadata","page":"Introduction","text":"Every key/value pair from the file is preserved in s.metadata, a Dict{String, Any} keyed on the raw key from the file:\n\ns.metadata[\"NPOINTS\"]     # \"12447\"\ns.metadata[\"FIRSTX\"]      # \"999.9101\"\ns.metadata[\"LASTX\"]       # \"7000.335\"\ns.metadata[\"RESOLUTION\"]  # \"4\"\n\nValues are stored as strings — they aren't converted to numbers automatically. The main header fields (TITLE, DATA TYPE, XUNITS, YUNITS, DATE, TIME, SPECTROMETER/DATA SYSTEM) are already accessible directly on the struct, so is used metadata for less common keys like instrument settings (laser power, detector type, integration count, etc.). See File formats for the per-instrument key list.","title":"Metadata"},{"category":"section","location":"#Checking-the-instrument","page":"Introduction","text":"Three functions check what kind of spectrum is loaded:\n\nisftir(s)     # true for DATA TYPE == \"INFRARED SPECTRUM\"\nisraman(s)    # true for DATA TYPE == \"RAMAN SPECTRUM\"\nisuvvis(s)    # true for DATA TYPE == \"UV/VIS SPECTRUM\"\n\nUse them to branch:\n\nif isftir(s)\n    # wavenumber-domain analysis\nelseif israman(s)\n    # Raman-shift analysis\nend\n\nor to filter a collection:\n\nftir_only = filter(isftir, spectra)","title":"Checking the instrument"},{"category":"section","location":"#Plotting","page":"Introduction","text":"With Makie loaded, you can plot a spectrum in one line:\n\nusing JASCOFiles, CairoMakie\n\ns = JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\")\nfig, ax, ln = plot(s)\nfig\n\nplot(s) fills in the axis labels and title from s, and reverses the x-axis for FTIR so wavenumbers decrease left-to-right (the convention used by most instrument software). Override any default via an axis NamedTuple; other keyword arguments are forwarded to Makie's lines:\n\nplot(s; color = :tomato)\nplot(s; axis = (xreversed = false, title = \"My sample\"))\n\nFor full control, s.x and s.y are plain vectors, so any plotting package works. xlabel(s) and ylabel(s) produce nicely formatted labels (e.g. \"Wavenumber (cm⁻¹)\", \"Transmittance (%)\") for any library:\n\nfig, ax, ln = lines(s.x, s.y;\n    axis = (xlabel = xlabel(s), ylabel = ylabel(s), title = s.title))","title":"Plotting"},{"category":"section","location":"#DataFrames-and-CSV","page":"Introduction","text":"A JASCOSpectrum plugs into the Tables.jl ecosystem with :x and :y columns. DataFrame, CSV.write, Arrow.write, and other Tables consumers work directly:\n\nusing JASCOFiles, DataFrames\n\ns = JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\")\ndf = DataFrame(s)            # columns :x and :y\n\nusing JASCOFiles, CSV\n\nCSV.write(\"sample_xy.csv\", JASCOSpectrum(\"sample.csv\"))\n\nYou never need to using Tables yourself — DataFrames, CSV, and friends pull it in transitively, and the package extension loads as soon as both JASCOFiles and a Tables consumer are in the same session.\n\nFor labelled headers when exporting, rename after conversion:\n\ndf = rename!(DataFrame(s), :x => :wavenumber, :y => :absorbance)\nCSV.write(\"sample_named.csv\", df)","title":"DataFrames and CSV"},{"category":"section","location":"#Issues-and-contributions","page":"Introduction","text":"If you run into a JASCO file this package mis-parses — especially one from a firmware version or instrument line not yet covered — please open an issue at github.com/garrekstemo/JASCOFiles.jl/issues. A minimal excerpt of the offending file is the most helpful thing to attach.","title":"Issues and contributions"},{"category":"module","location":"#JASCOFiles.JASCOFiles","page":"Introduction","text":"JASCOFiles\n\nRead CSV files exported from JASCO spectrometers (FTIR, Raman, UV-Vis) into a concrete JASCOSpectrum struct. The parser auto-detects the delimiter (comma for FTIR/Raman, tab for V-series UV-Vis) and decodes SHIFT-JIS metadata by default.\n\nCall JASCOSpectrum(path) to read a file, then access .x, .y, .xunits, .yunits, .datatype, and .metadata on the result. Use isftir, israman, or isuvvis to dispatch on instrument type.\n\n\n\n\n\n","title":"JASCOFiles.JASCOFiles"}]
}
